Part I - (Flights Dataset Exploration)¶

by Syed F Hussaini¶

Introduction¶

Flights dataset is Reporting Carrier On-Time Performace Data retrieved from Buerau of Transportation statistics website via this link. This dataset contains 2,000,000 records and 109 features on flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays from 1987 to 2022.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In [15]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='DepDelay', y='ArrDelay', data=df, alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Relationship between Departure and Arrival Delays')
plt.xlabel('Departure Delay (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Arrival Delay (minutes)')
plt.show()
  • Strong positive correlation
    • Clear linear relationship between departure delays and arrival delays. As the departure delay increases, the arrival delay also tends to increase. This is expected as flights that leave later than scheduled often arrive later than scheduled.
  • Data Clustering
    • Most data points are clustered around the origin, indicating that the majority of flights either depart on time or with minor delays and similarly arrive on time or with only slight delays.
  • Outliers
    • There are a few outliers, particularly flights with very high departure delays that also have very high arrival delays. There are also some data points with negative values for both departure and arrival delays, which represent flights that departed and arrived earlier than scheduled.
  • Anomalous Points
    • There are some anomalies where the arrival delays are negatives even though the departure delays are positive, and vice versa. This may suggest that some flights managed to make up time in the air despite departing late, or encountered issues after departing early.
In [16]:
# Filter out rows where any of these specific columns have NaN values
delay_data = df[['Distance', 'CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay']]
delay_data = delay_data.dropna()

# Set up the matplotlib figure and axes
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(15, 10))
fig.suptitle('Relationship Between Flight Distance and Types of Delays')

# Flatten the axis array for easier iteration
axs = axs.flatten()

# List of delay types
delay_types = ['CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay']

# Create a scatter plot for each type of delay
for i, delay_type in enumerate(delay_types):
    sns.scatterplot(x='Distance', y=delay_type, data=delay_data, ax=axs[i], alpha=0.1)
    axs[i].set_title(f'{delay_type} vs. Distance')
    axs[i].set_xlabel('Distance (miles)')
    axs[i].set_ylabel(f'{delay_type} (minutes)')

# Hide any unused axes if there are any
for j in range(i + 1, len(axs)):
    axs[j].set_visible(False)

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95])  # Adjust layout to make room for the main title
plt.show()

  • Carrier Delay vs. Distance

    • Observation: There is a visible accumulation of points at the lower range of distances, with carrier delays concentrated in the shorter flights. However, there are several significant delays extending up to the maximum distance.
    • Interpretation: This suggests that while carrier-related delays can occur at any flight length, they might be more frequent or pronounced on shorter flights. The reasons could include logistical or operational issues that are not necessarily mitigated by longer flights.

  • Weather Delay vs. Distance

    • Observation: Weather delays show a similar trend to carrier delays, with a dense clustering at shorter distances and a spread of points across all distances.
    • Interpretation: Weather delays appear to affect flights of all distances, but the higher frequency at shorter distances might be influenced by more frequent take-offs and landings, which are more susceptible to weather conditions.

  • NAS Delay vs. Distance

    • Observation: NAS delays are more densely populated at the lower end of the distance scale but have a relatively consistent presence across all distances.
    • Interpretation: NAS delays, which are related to the management of the national airspace, affect flights broadly, regardless of distance. This could reflect airspace congestion that impacts flights similarly irrespective of flight length.

  • Security Delay vs. Distance

    • Observation: Security delays are generally low across all distances, with very few outliers showing significant delay.
    • Interpretation: This type of delay does not show a clear correlation with distance, suggesting that security issues are relatively uniform and not heavily influenced by the length of the flight.

  • Late Aircraft Delay vs. Distance

    • Observation: There is a large number of late aircraft delays concentrated at shorter distances, with fewer occurrences as distance increases.
    • Interpretation: This pattern may indicate that shorter flights, which are typically more frequent and have quicker turnaround times, are more vulnerable to delays caused by late-arriving aircraft. The impact of these delays diminishes over longer distances where scheduling might allow more buffer time.

  • Variability in delays
    • The spread (IQR) of departure delays varies significantly between different airlines. Some airlines show a wide range of delays (large IQR), indicating inconsistency in their departure times, while others display a more compact IQR, suggesting more reliable departure performance.
  • Outliers
    • Many airlines have outliers indicating extremely long delays. The presence and extent of these outliers vary, with some airlines exhibiting more frequent and severe departure delays than others.
  • Median Delay Differences
    • The median departure delay (indicated by the line within the box) also varies across airlines. Some airlines typically have near-zero or very short median delays, indicating punctuality, while others have higher medians, suggesting frequent delays.

    • There is a significant difference in operational scale among airlines. For example, (like AA, DL, and UA), show much higher numbers throughout the year, indicating large, possibly global networks. In contrast, smaller regional airlines like KH and YX exhibit far fewer flights.

    • Some airlines maintain relatively consistent flight volumes across months (e.g., AS, B6), while others show more pronounced variability (e.g., NK, F9), which could be due to different business models or market focuses.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Relationship between Departure Delays and Arrival Delays:
    • A strong positive correlation exists between departure delays and arrival delays, indicating that flights that depart late tend to arrive late. The scatter plot shows clustering of points along a line with a positive slope. Some outliers where flights show minimal or no arrival delays despite significant departure delays might be due to making up time during the flight or due to generous scheduling allowances.
  • Distribution of Departure Delays by Airline:
    • The box plots reveal significant differences in median departure delays across airlines. Some airlines consistently show higher delays, suggesting operational inefficiencies or different policy responses to similar conditions. Others display a wide range of delays (high interquartile range), indicating inconsistency in their departure times, while some have tighter distributions but many outliers, suggesting generally good performance occasionally marred by significant delays.
  • Monthly Flight Frequency by Airline:
    • The heatmap shows higher flight frequencies during peak travel months like June, July, and December, indicating how airlines scale operations in response to demand. Some airlines display strong seasonal spikes more than others, which could be due to the specific markets they serve, such as airlines focusing on leisure destinations peaking in summer.
  • Relationship between Flight Distance and Types of Delays:
    • Longer flights might experience fewer departure delays but more airtime delays due to factors like air traffic or weather conditions encountered en route. Conversely, shorter flights might frequently experience ground-related delays at congested airports, highlighting different challenges faced by flights of varying distances.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • Business Strategies in Heatmap Visualization:
    • The heatmap indicates differing business strategies among airlines. For example, airlines with minor fluctuations in flight frequencies might be focusing on business travelers who require consistent, year-round service. Meanwhile, those with significant peaks and troughs might be capitalizing on seasonal tourist traffic, adjusting their capacities to meet fluctuating demands effectively.
  • Operational Efficiency and Network Size:
    • Larger airlines or those with extensive networks might have the resources or strategies in place to manage or mitigate the impact of potential delays more effectively than smaller airlines. This is reflected in how compact their delay distributions are, despite managing a high volume of flights. Conversely, smaller or budget airlines may struggle more with operational disruptions, leading to more frequent or severe delays.

In [22]:
# Scatter plot with improvements
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
custom_palette =sns.color_palette("viridis", n_colors=summary_data.shape[0])
sns.scatterplot(data=summary_data, x='TotalFlights', y='AverageDelay', hue='Year', size='Year',
                sizes=(50, 250), palette=custom_palette, alpha=0.8)

# Adding a LOESS(Locally Estimated Scatterplot Smoothing) curve to show trend
sns.regplot(data=summary_data, x='TotalFlights', y='AverageDelay', scatter=False, color='red', lowess=True)

plt.title('Relationship Between Flight Volume, Average Delay, and Year', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Total Number of Flights', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Average Delay (Minutes)', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title='Year', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)  # Adding grid for better readability
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to make room for the legend outside the plot area
plt.show()
  • Yearly trends:
    • The plot uses a viridis as color palette, which transitions from darker to lighter colors. Early years are represented in darker tones and appear to have fewer flights and lower delays. As time progresses,the colors lighten. And both the number of flights and the delays increase, particularly noticeable in the latest years shown in yellow.
  • Trend over time:
    • A LOESS curve is added to highlight the overall trend between total number of flights and average delay. The curve shows a general trend where delays decrease as the number of flights increases up to a certain point, after which the delays begin to increase sharply. This suggests a non-linear relationship where initially, increased flight operations might be managed efficiently, but beyond a certain threshold, the system gets overwhelmed, leading to higher delays.
  • Flight volumne against delays:
    • The size of each point correlates with the number of flights, giving a visual representation of air traffic volume. Years with larger points generally have higher delays, illustrating the impact of increased flight volumes on delay times.

Conclusions¶

What are the peak travel times in the year?¶

Ordinarily, travel trends correspond to holiday seasons and summer months, where increased travel demand pressures the existing infrastructure. The "Monthly Flight Frequency by Airline" plot highlights peak travel times, particularly noting increased flight volumes during specific months like June, July, and December. This trend suggests that summer and winter holidays are peak travel periods, likely driven by vacation travel and holiday visits.

What are the common reasons for delays and cancellations?¶

The analysis of delay causes has shown that primary areas of concern like weather and carrier issues which lead to operational disruptions. The "Frequency of Cancellation Reasons" plot illustrates that weather (Code B) and carrier issues (Code A) are the most common reasons for cancellations, with weather being the predominant factor. Additionally, the "Annual Trends in Delay Causes" and various delay-related scatter plots indicate that carrier and weather delays are significant contributors to overall delays, alongside National Air System (NAS) delays.

How does the flight distance affect the duration of delays and overall flight time?¶

The "Relationship Between Flight Distance and Types of Delays" scatter plots show that longer flights tend to have more significant airtime delays, possibly due to factors encountered en route such as airspace congestion or weather conditions. Shorter flights frequently experience ground-related delays, particularly at congested airports.

What are the changes to cause of delay features over the years of 2003 to 2022?¶

 The trend analysis from the faceted graphs clearly indicates how different factors influencing delays have evolved. The "Annual Trends in Delay Causes" plots reveal fluctuations in delay causes over the years. Notable is the spike in security delays post-2001, with a general decrease in recent years except for periodic spikes, possibly reflecting changes in security measures and regulations over time. Carrier and NAS delays exhibit variability, potentially linked to changes in industry practices and infrastructure enhancements.

Overall Conclusion¶

The integration of data from these plots enables a comprehensive understanding that as flight volumes have increased, the industry’s ability to manage delays has been strained, particularly in operational areas such as carrier efficiency and aircraft turnover. Although advancements have mitigated some types of delays, the overall capacity to handle peak volumes efficiently remains a challenge. Addressing these operational inefficiencies, possibly through technological innovations or enhanced management strategies, is crucial for improving overall performance and reducing delays, thereby enhancing passenger satisfaction and operational reliability.

  • Peak travel periods align with holiday seasons, reflecting higher passenger volumes.
  • Weather and carrier inefficiencies are primary factors for flight delays and cancellations, highlighting areas where airlines could focus improvements.
  • Flight distance significantly impacts the nature of delays, with longer distances more susceptible to en route delays than shorter ones.
  • Over the years, regulatory changes, technological advancements, and carrier policies have influenced the patterns of delays and cancellations.

This holistic conclusion not only answers the specific research questions but also provides actionable insights for stakeholders in the airline industry to target for improvements.
